political loyalties and allowed counterinsurgent armed groups to implement political cleansing against civilians perceived as loyal to insurgents.Combining evidence collected from remote archives, more than two hundred interviews, and quantitative data from the government's displacement registry, Steele connects Colombia's political development and the course of its civil war to purposeful displacement. By introducing the concepts of collective targeting and political cleansing, Steele extends what we already know about patterns of ethnic cleansing to cases where expulsion of civilians from their communities is based on nonethnic traits.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aForced migrationzColombiaxHistory. 0aPolitical persecutionzColombiaxHistory. 0aPolitical violencezColombiaxHistory. 4aInternational Studies. 4aLatin American & Caribbean Studies. 4aPolitical Science & Political History. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Security (National & International).2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2017z978311066587140uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781501709753zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501709753423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781501709753.jpg  a978-3-11-066587-1  Cornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2017b2017  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK